msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:115
msgid "Any masked values in x is propagated in y, and vice-versa."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:117
msgid "The solution minimizes the squared error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:119
msgid ""
"E = \\sum_{j=0}^k |p(x_j) - y_j|^2\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:122
msgid "in the equations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:124
msgid ""
"x[0]**n * p[0] + ... + x[0] * p[n-1] + p[n] = y[0]\n"
"x[1]**n * p[0] + ... + x[1] * p[n-1] + p[n] = y[1]\n"
"...\n"
"x[k]**n * p[0] + ... + x[k] * p[n-1] + p[n] = y[k]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:129
msgid "The coefficient matrix of the coefficients `p` is a Vandermonde matrix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:131
msgid ""
"`polyfit` issues a `~exceptions.RankWarning` when the least-squares fit is "
"badly conditioned. This implies that the best fit is not well-defined due to "
"numerical error. The results may be improved by lowering the polynomial "
"degree or by replacing `x` by `x` - `x`.mean(). The `rcond` parameter can "
"also be set to a value smaller than its default, but the resulting fit may "
"be spurious: including contributions from the small singular values can add "
"numerical noise to the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/ma/extras.py:docstring
#: of numpy.ma.extras.polyfit:139
msgid ""
"Note that fitting polynomial coefficients is inherently badly conditioned "
"when the degree of the polynomial is large or the interval of sample points "
"is badly centered. The quality of the fit should always be checked in these "
"cases. When polynomial fits are not satisfactory, splines may be a good "
"alternative."
msgstr ""

